<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1892-06-10T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1892-06-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="148" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d148">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wharton</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Phelps</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1892-06-10"><hi rend="italic">June 10,
                            1892</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 433.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                        dispatch No. 447, of the 22d ultimo, concerning the protection of American
                        inventors in Germany.</p>
                    <p>The Department’s No. 420, of May 19, 1892, sufficiently answers the further
                        statements of the imperial secretary of state for foreign affairs, in
                        relation to the nonpublication of the notification in question, pending the
                        conclusion of a trade-mark treaty which will definitely adjust the
                        matter.</p>
                    <p>I am, sir,</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">William F. Wharton</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>